TITLE: Shipping Companies Added Capacity, but Now Containers Are Stuck in Port
SUMMARY: Ship operators have added millions of containers, but supply-chain snarls persist as ports, rails and warehouses struggle to handle the volume.

TITLE: Should States Adopt Right-to-Repair Laws? Pros and Cons
SUMMARY: Advocates of the laws say manufacturers are protecting themselves. Opponents say the laws will hurt consumers. The two sides square off in a debate.

TITLE: Companies Rush to Cash In on EPA's Methane Rules
SUMMARY: New Environmental Protection Agency rules promise to give a significant boost to what is becoming known as the methane mitigation industry.

TITLE: Danone to Fly Formula to the U.S. for Babies With Allergies
SUMMARY: The French food giant said about half a million cans of specialized medical formula made by its Nutricia business will be flown into the U.S. in the coming weeks, as part of a broader push to alleviate shortages faced by babies with allergies.

TITLE: Tech Billionaire Brings Down Breakup Plan by Australia's Biggest Polluter
SUMMARY: Mike Cannon-Brookes had opposed AGL Energy’s effort to spin off its coal-fired power plants. The scrapping of the plans handed a win to environmentalists who want a faster shift to cleaner energy.

TITLE: China's Slowdown Poses Credibility Test for Economic Data
SUMMARY: An economic slowdown leads some economists to question how closely the flow of official data will stick to economic reality as the rest of the year progresses.

TITLE: 17 States Where Unemployment Is at Record Lows
SUMMARY: The unemployment rate hit record lows in 17 states in the Midwest, South and Mountain West in April, a sign of a labor market where there are too few workers to keep pace with consumer spending and employer demand.

TITLE: Europe's Bid to Kick Russian Natural Gas Runs Into Opposition
SUMMARY: The European Union has a plan to stop buying Russian natural gas within five years by installing wind turbines and solar panels on a massive scale, but a gauntlet of environmental groups, local opposition and bureaucracy stands in the way.

TITLE: Dogs or Cats: Which Animal Is More Effective in Ads?
SUMMARY: The answer depends on what type of product is being promoted.

TITLE: Robots Pick Up More Work at Busy Factories
SUMMARY: Rising wages and worker shortages, compounded by increases in Covid-19-related absenteeism, are changing some manufacturers’ attitudes about robots.
